---
import TheLeagueLayout from '../../layouts/TheLeagueLayout.astro';

---

<TheLeagueLayout title="About This Project | The League">
  <main class="about-page">

    <!-- ===== HERO ===== -->
    <header class="about-hero">
      <div class="about-hero__eyebrow">
        <span class="about-tag">Production Case Study</span>
        <span class="about-dot">·</span>
        <span class="about-hero__date">2025 – Present</span>
      </div>

      <h1 class="about-hero__title">Most AI experiments live in notebooks.<br>This one lives in production.</h1>

      <p class="about-hero__deck">
        A dynasty fantasy football site built from scratch that 16 real people use every
        single week to make real decisions. It's also a live test for figuring out where AI
        actually helps — and where it just gets in the way. Not a demo. Not a toy.
        A real app with real stakes.
      </p>

      <div class="about-hero__stack">
        <span class="about-stack-item">Astro + TypeScript</span>
        <span class="about-stack-dot">·</span>
        <span class="about-stack-item">MFL API Integration</span>
        <span class="about-stack-dot">·</span>
        <span class="about-stack-item">Claude API</span>
        <span class="about-stack-dot">·</span>
        <span class="about-stack-item">Structured AI Scaffolding</span>
        <span class="about-stack-dot">·</span>
        <span class="about-stack-item">Dynasty Contract Engine</span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <!-- ===== STATS STRIP ===== -->
    <div class="about-stats">
      <div class="about-stats__item">
        <div class="about-stats__value">15+</div>
        <div class="about-stats__label">Years of player salary data on file</div>
      </div>
      <div class="about-stats__item">
        <div class="about-stats__value">$45M</div>
        <div class="about-stats__label">Salary cap — exact, enforced, tested</div>
      </div>
      <div class="about-stats__item">
        <div class="about-stats__value">2</div>
        <div class="about-stats__label">Leagues on one codebase</div>
      </div>
      <div class="about-stats__item">
        <div class="about-stats__value">0</div>
        <div class="about-stats__label">Times AI touches the rule-based math</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="about-body">

      <!-- ===== 01: THE PROBLEM DOMAIN ===== -->
      <section class="about-section">
        <div class="about-section-header">
          <span class="about-section-num">01</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="about-section-title">The Problem Domain</h2>
            <p class="about-section-sub">Why dynasty fantasy football turned out to be a perfect testing ground for AI</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="about-two-col">
          <div class="about-prose">
            <p>
              Dynasty fantasy football isn't the same game most people know. You don't redraft
              every year. You own players across multiple seasons, sign them to multi-year contracts,
              manage a salary cap, and plan your roster the way an NFL front office would —
              except you're doing it in a group chat at 11pm on a Tuesday, which is its own
              kind of decision-making environment.
            </p>
            <p>
              It also turns out to be a great place to test AI, because two totally different
              kinds of problems are happening at the same time: ones with <strong>exact right answers</strong>,
              and ones that are more like <strong>educated guesses</strong>.
            </p>
            <p>
              The salary cap is $45M. Not roughly. Not "around there." Going over disqualifies
              your roster. That's not a place for AI to weigh in — it's just math. But figuring
              out whether a 27-year-old running back is worth a 3-year, $9M contract? That involves
              injury history, usage trends, age, offensive scheme, and a dozen other things
              all at once. That's exactly where AI can help.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="about-domain-box">
            <div class="about-domain-type">
              <div class="about-domain-type__label">Hard Constraints</div>
              <div class="about-domain-type__items">
                <div class="about-domain-item">Salary cap: exactly $45,000,000</div>
                <div class="about-domain-item">Roster limit: exactly 28 players</div>
                <div class="about-domain-item">Contract escalation: exactly 10%/yr</div>
                <div class="about-domain-item">Franchise tag rules: explicitly defined</div>
              </div>
              <div class="about-domain-type__verdict about-domain-type__verdict--det">Pure math. No AI needed.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="about-domain-type about-domain-type--prob">
              <div class="about-domain-type__label">Best Guesses</div>
              <div class="about-domain-type__items">
                <div class="about-domain-item">How fast players decline with age</div>
                <div class="about-domain-item">What a fair trade actually looks like</div>
                <div class="about-domain-item">What a player will actually sell for</div>
                <div class="about-domain-item">Which free agents fill our biggest needs</div>
              </div>
              <div class="about-domain-type__verdict about-domain-type__verdict--prob">AI helps here. Answers get checked.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== 02: ARCHITECTURE ===== -->
      <section class="about-section">
        <div class="about-section-header">
          <span class="about-section-num">02</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="about-section-title">How It's Built: The Big Separation</h2>
            <p class="about-section-sub">The single most important decision made early on — and why it paid off</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="about-prose">
          <p>
            The most important decision made early — and never changed — was this: keep the
            exact math completely separate from AI's judgment calls. Not just in theory, but
            enforced in the actual code. It sounds simple. In reality, it takes discipline to
            stick to as new features pile up and the easy answer is always "just let AI handle it."
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="about-arch">
          <div class="about-arch__layer about-arch__layer--det">
            <div class="about-arch__layer-header">
              <span class="about-arch__layer-title">The Math Layer</span>
              <span class="about-arch__layer-badge">TypeScript · Fully Tested</span>
            </div>
            <div class="about-arch__modules">
              <div class="about-arch__module">
                <div class="about-arch__module-name">Salary Engine</div>
                <div class="about-arch__module-desc"><code>salary-calculations.ts</code> — cap math, salary escalation, dead money</div>
              </div>
              <div class="about-arch__module">
                <div class="about-arch__module-name">MFL API Layer</div>
                <div class="about-arch__module-desc">Pulls data from the fantasy football API and cleans it up before anything uses it</div>
              </div>
              <div class="about-arch__module">
                <div class="about-arch__module-name">Contract Logic</div>
                <div class="about-arch__module-desc">Handles franchise tags, expired contracts, and how much cap space they hold</div>
              </div>
              <div class="about-arch__module">
                <div class="about-arch__module-name">Year Rollover</div>
                <div class="about-arch__module-desc">Figures out which year is "now" for league purposes — testable via <code>?testDate=</code></div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="about-arch__bridge">
            <div class="about-arch__bridge-label">Clean Data Handoff</div>
            <div class="about-arch__bridge-desc">
              Checked, verified facts pass upward. AI gets clean information — not raw messy API responses.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="about-arch__layer about-arch__layer--prob">
            <div class="about-arch__layer-header">
              <span class="about-arch__layer-title">The AI Layer</span>
              <span class="about-arch__layer-badge">Claude API · Guided · Checked</span>
            </div>
            <div class="about-arch__modules">
              <div class="about-arch__module">
                <div class="about-arch__module-name">Trade Analysis</div>
                <div class="about-arch__module-desc">Figures out if a trade is fair and who's getting the better end of the deal</div>
              </div>
              <div class="about-arch__module">
                <div class="about-arch__module-name">Auction Predictor</div>
                <div class="about-arch__module-desc">Past results + what teams need + how many players are left → price estimate</div>
              </div>
              <div class="about-arch__module">
                <div class="about-arch__module-name">Free Agent Fit</div>
                <div class="about-arch__module-desc">Ranks which available players would help your roster the most right now</div>
              </div>
              <div class="about-arch__module">
                <div class="about-arch__module-name">Decision Support</div>
                <div class="about-arch__module-desc">Summarizes the situation, lays out the options, flags what could go wrong</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <blockquote class="about-quote">
          "Letting AI do the salary cap math would make the app worse, not better.
          The question isn't whether AI is smart enough — it's whether this is even the
          right kind of question to ask AI in the first place."
        </blockquote>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== 03: AI SCAFFOLDING ===== -->
      <section class="about-section">
        <div class="about-section-header">
          <span class="about-section-num">03</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="about-section-title">How AI Is Used</h2>
            <p class="about-section-sub">Every AI feature follows the same four-step setup — no freestyle chatbots allowed</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="about-prose">
          <p>
            Every AI feature on this site follows the same four-step setup. The goal is
            simple: always know what AI is doing, be able to check its work, and fix it
            when it's wrong. That takes more planning upfront, but it pays off.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="about-scaffold">
          <div class="about-scaffold__item">
            <div class="about-scaffold__num">1</div>
            <div class="about-scaffold__content">
              <div class="about-scaffold__title">Only Give AI What It Needs</div>
              <div class="about-scaffold__body">
                Every time AI gets asked something, it only receives the data that's
                relevant to that specific question — not the entire database. Asking about
                a trade? AI gets that player's contract, your team's cap space, and some
                recent history. Nothing more. What information AI gets is a decision,
                not an afterthought.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="about-scaffold__item">
            <div class="about-scaffold__num">2</div>
            <div class="about-scaffold__content">
              <div class="about-scaffold__title">Ask Specific Questions, Get Useful Answers</div>
              <div class="about-scaffold__body">
                AI questions are specific, not vague. "Given this contract, age, and last
                season's stats — rate this player's trade value 1–10 and name the three
                biggest reasons" gives you something you can actually check. "Tell me about
                this player" gives you a wall of text that sounds plausible but is hard
                to verify.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="about-scaffold__item">
            <div class="about-scaffold__num">3</div>
            <div class="about-scaffold__content">
              <div class="about-scaffold__title">Know How It Can Go Wrong Before It Does</div>
              <div class="about-scaffold__body">
                Before any AI feature goes live, the ways it can fail are written down first.
                What does a wrong-but-confident answer look like? When should you not trust it?
                What happens if it breaks completely? Writing this down before launch means
                you're testing for problems you've already thought through — not stumbling
                onto them when 16 people are counting on the app.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="about-scaffold__item">
            <div class="about-scaffold__num">4</div>
            <div class="about-scaffold__content">
              <div class="about-scaffold__title">Show Your Work</div>
              <div class="about-scaffold__body">
                Every AI answer shows what data it used. A trade recommendation shows
                the salary numbers side by side. An auction estimate shows what similar
                players sold for in past years. If the answer is wrong, you can trace
                it back to bad data — which is much easier to fix than bad reasoning.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== 04: THE META-SYSTEM ===== -->
      <section class="about-section">
        <div class="about-section-header">
          <span class="about-section-num">04</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="about-section-title">AI Builds It Too</h2>
            <p class="about-section-sub">AI isn't just a feature in the app — it helps write the app itself</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="about-two-col about-two-col--wide-text">
          <div class="about-prose">
            <p>
              The most interesting part of this project isn't any one feature. It's how
              the whole thing gets built. AI doesn't just power the features inside the
              app — it's part of the process of writing the code itself.
            </p>
            <p>
              The <strong>AI Insights System</strong> is a running notebook of everything
              learned along the way — organized into files by topic (design patterns, API
              quirks, component rules) and by feature. Before every coding session, the
              relevant notes get loaded in. After, anything new gets written back.
            </p>
            <p>
              This means AI gets smarter about the project over time instead of forgetting
              everything between sessions. It's not starting from scratch each time — it
              has notes. The knowledge stacks up.
            </p>
            <p>
              The same rules that apply to using AI in the product apply here too: give
              it only what it needs, keep a clear format, and make sure mistakes get
              caught and fixed instead of quietly piling up.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="about-insights-viz">
            <div class="about-insights-header">AI Insights System</div>
            <div class="about-insights-flow">
              <div class="about-insights-node about-insights-node--trigger">
                Task begins
              </div>
              <div class="about-insights-arrow">↓</div>
              <div class="about-insights-node about-insights-node--load">
                Load relevant domain + feature files into context
              </div>
              <div class="about-insights-arrow">↓</div>
              <div class="about-insights-node about-insights-node--work">
                AI executes task with accumulated project knowledge
              </div>
              <div class="about-insights-arrow">↓</div>
              <div class="about-insights-node about-insights-node--write">
                New learnings written back to corpus
              </div>
              <div class="about-insights-arrow about-insights-arrow--loop">↑ compounds</div>
            </div>
            <div class="about-insights-files">
              <div class="about-insights-file">domains/design-system.md</div>
              <div class="about-insights-file">domains/mfl-api.md</div>
              <div class="about-insights-file">domains/frontend.md</div>
              <div class="about-insights-file">features/trade-builder.md</div>
              <div class="about-insights-file">features/auction-predictor.md</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <blockquote class="about-quote">
          "The way the site is built runs on the same principles as the site itself:
          focused information, clear format, and a feedback loop that improves over time.
          How it's built is the point."
        </blockquote>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== 05: RELIABILITY ===== -->
      <section class="about-section">
        <div class="about-section-header">
          <span class="about-section-num">05</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="about-section-title">What We Learned the Hard Way</h2>
            <p class="about-section-sub">Two patterns that only show up when real people use your AI features for real</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="about-prose">
          <p>
            Two patterns showed up that you'd never catch in a test environment — only after
            a full season of real decisions with real consequences when the answers were wrong.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="about-reliability-grid">
          <div class="about-reliability-card">
            <div class="about-reliability-card__eyebrow">Pattern 01</div>
            <div class="about-reliability-card__title">Narrow Questions Beat Wide-Open Ones</div>
            <div class="about-reliability-card__body">
              <p>
                Asking AI a specific question works better than asking a broad one. Not because
                AI is smarter with less to think about — but because a narrow question makes it
                easier to spot a wrong answer. "Rate this trade value 1–10 and name the three
                biggest factors" gives you something you can verify. "What do you think about
                this player?" sounds useful but hides bad answers until they've already
                cost you something.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="about-reliability-card">
            <div class="about-reliability-card__eyebrow">Pattern 02</div>
            <div class="about-reliability-card__title">Bad Data Is Usually the Problem, Not Bad AI</div>
            <div class="about-reliability-card__body">
              <p>
                When AI gives a wrong answer, the data fed to it is usually the culprit —
                not the AI itself. Outdated stats, a salary that's off by a year, a player
                who got traded mid-season. Given clean, accurate data, AI's reasoning
                is usually fine. This means keeping the underlying data accurate matters
                just as much as anything AI does with it.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== 06: ITERATION ===== -->
      <section class="about-section">
        <div class="about-section-header">
          <span class="about-section-num">06</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="about-section-title">Ship Small, Learn Fast, Repeat</h2>
            <p class="about-section-sub">The site is built the same way it works — one piece at a time, always with the next step in mind</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="about-prose">
          <p>
            The same approach used to build AI features is used to build the whole site:
            be clear about what you're making, ship something small, see how it works,
            fix what's broken, and repeat. Every feature is built to work together with
            the others — not as a one-time standalone thing.
          </p>
          <p>
            The What's New section — which updates every week with real screenshots and
            plain-English explanations — isn't just documentation. It's a discipline. If
            you can't write clearly what changed and why it matters, you probably don't
            fully understand what you built yet.
          </p>
          <p>
            Every piece of this site was built with the Auction Price Predictor in mind
            as the eventual goal. Features don't ship just because they work — they ship
            when they fit into the larger system. Being able to plug into other features
            isn't optional, it's a requirement from day one.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="about-timeline">
          <div class="about-timeline__phase">
            <div class="about-timeline__label">Foundation</div>
            <div class="about-timeline__items">
              <span class="about-tl-item">MFL API integration</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">Salary engine</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">Roster hub</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">Contract logic</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="about-timeline__arrow">→</div>
          <div class="about-timeline__phase">
            <div class="about-timeline__label">Decision Tools</div>
            <div class="about-timeline__items">
              <span class="about-tl-item">Trade builder</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">Free agent view</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">League planner</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">Draft predictor</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="about-timeline__arrow">→</div>
          <div class="about-timeline__phase">
            <div class="about-timeline__label">Analytics Layer</div>
            <div class="about-timeline__items">
              <span class="about-tl-item">Salary MVPs</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">Dead money</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">League summary</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">Historical analysis</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="about-timeline__arrow">→</div>
          <div class="about-timeline__phase about-timeline__phase--next">
            <div class="about-timeline__label">Predictive System</div>
            <div class="about-timeline__items">
              <span class="about-tl-item">Auction predictor</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">AI trade framing</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">Value signals</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">Scarcity model</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== 07: WHATS NEXT ===== -->
      <section class="about-section">
        <div class="about-section-header">
          <span class="about-section-num">07</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="about-section-title">The Auction Price Predictor</h2>
            <p class="about-section-sub">What this entire system was designed to support</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="about-prose">
          <p>
            Dynasty auctions are one of the hardest things to predict in fantasy sports. You're
            not just asking "is this player good?" — you're asking "what will someone actually
            pay for this player, right now, with these 12 managers, given who's already been
            sold?" The same player can go for double or half the price depending on when they
            show up in the auction and how desperate people are at that position.
          </p>
          <p>
            That's exactly the kind of messy, multi-factor problem where AI can actually help
            — as long as it's sitting on top of a solid foundation that knows exactly how much
            cap space each team has left, which positions still need to be filled, and what
            players have actually cost in previous years.
          </p>
          <p>
            Every decision made building this site — how the layers split, how data flows,
            how shared tools are built — was made with this feature in mind. The groundwork
            is done. This is what comes next.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="about-predictor-box">
          <div class="about-predictor-box__title">Auction Predictor: System Inputs</div>
          <div class="about-predictor-box__grid">
            <div class="about-predictor-input">
              <div class="about-predictor-input__label">Historical Salary Data</div>
              <div class="about-predictor-input__desc">15 years of what players actually sold for, sorted by year and position</div>
            </div>
            <div class="about-predictor-input">
              <div class="about-predictor-input__label">Roster Context</div>
              <div class="about-predictor-input__desc">Exactly how much cap space each team has left and which positions they still need to fill</div>
            </div>
            <div class="about-predictor-input">
              <div class="about-predictor-input__label">Positional Scarcity</div>
              <div class="about-predictor-input__desc">How many good options are left at each position as the auction winds down</div>
            </div>
            <div class="about-predictor-input">
              <div class="about-predictor-input__label">Player Signal</div>
              <div class="about-predictor-input__desc">Age, contract situation, recent performance, and what NFL team they're on</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="about-predictor-box__output">
            <span class="about-predictor-box__output-label">Output →</span>
            <span class="about-predictor-box__output-val">A price range for what the player will likely sell for, plus how that affects each team's roster situation</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== 08: CROSS-STACK ===== -->
      <section class="about-section">
        <div class="about-section-header">
          <span class="about-section-num">08</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="about-section-title">Doing It All Yourself</h2>
            <p class="about-section-sub">When there's no one to hand off to, you learn every part of the system</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="about-prose">
          <p>
            Most teams have specialists. Designers hand off to engineers. Engineers hand off to
            data teams. Business people delegate everything technical. This project had none of
            that. Every part of it — design, code, data, AI, content, strategy — had to be
            figured out and owned by one person.
          </p>
          <p>
            The result is that everything connects. How the site looks shapes how data is
            structured. How data is structured shapes what AI is told. What AI produces shapes
            what goes in the changelog. What's in the changelog shapes what gets built next.
            It's one system wearing different hats.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="about-crossstack-grid">
          <div class="about-cs-card">
            <div class="about-cs-card__discipline">Design System Tokens</div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__evidence">
              A full visual style system built from scratch — font sizes, colors, spacing, shadows —
              all stored as reusable variables. Both leagues share the same system, so fixing
              a design detail updates everywhere at once.
            </div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__artifact">tokens.css · design-system.astro</div>
          </div>

          <div class="about-cs-card">
            <div class="about-cs-card__discipline">Content Modeling</div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__evidence">
              The What's New section isn't just a blog — it's a structured data format with required
              fields, screenshot rules, and an automatic weekly rollup. If you skip any of it,
              the build breaks.
            </div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__artifact">whats-new.json · weekly-changelog-rollup.mjs</div>
          </div>

          <div class="about-cs-card">
            <div class="about-cs-card__discipline">Front-End Architecture</div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__evidence">
              The site is built with Astro and TypeScript. The same codebase powers two separate
              leagues — same components, same layout, zero copy-paste. PlayerCell, the Trade
              Builder, and the Player Modal are all reusable building blocks that work anywhere
              they're needed.
            </div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__artifact">TheLeagueLayout · league-context.ts</div>
          </div>

          <div class="about-cs-card">
            <div class="about-cs-card__discipline">Performance Engineering</div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__evidence">
              Data from the MFL API gets downloaded and saved at build time, so most pages don't
              have to fetch anything when you open them — they're already done. If a page needs
              live data, it asks for it, but that's the exception. Fast pages, no waiting.
            </div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__artifact">prerender = true · pnpm sync:all</div>
          </div>

          <div class="about-cs-card">
            <div class="about-cs-card__discipline">Analytics</div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__evidence">
              Dead Money Awards, Salary-Adjusted MVP, League Summary — these aren't just fun pages.
              They're built on shared math that other tools can reuse. The same salary calculations
              that power the Dead Money page also power the Trade Builder. Write it once, use it
              everywhere.
            </div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__artifact">salary-calculations.ts · dead-money.astro</div>
          </div>

          <div class="about-cs-card">
            <div class="about-cs-card__discipline">Building With Purpose</div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__evidence">
              Every feature gets built because it helps someone win: better cap decisions, smarter
              trades, sharper auction bids. The game strategy and the build plan live in the same
              document — so the answer to "what should we build next?" is always the same: whatever
              makes you more competitive.
            </div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__artifact">CLAUDE.md · Team Strategy section</div>
          </div>

          <div class="about-cs-card">
            <div class="about-cs-card__discipline">Finding Your Voice</div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__evidence">
              The What's New entries aren't just patch notes — they have a personality. Funny,
              specific, written like a person. There are actual rules about how to write them
              (yes, rules for changelog entries). Because if you can't explain what you built in
              a way that's worth reading, you might as well not have shipped it.
            </div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__artifact">whats-new.json · CLAUDE.md writing style guide</div>
          </div>

          <div class="about-cs-card">
            <div class="about-cs-card__discipline">Shipping Consistently</div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__evidence">
              Every release shows up on the homepage for a week. Bug fixes get grouped and posted
              every Monday automatically. Screenshots are required — the build fails without them.
              The whole system is set up so that shipping something and telling people about it
              are the same step.
            </div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__artifact">weekly-changelog-rollup.mjs · hero-resolver.ts</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <blockquote class="about-quote">
          "These aren't separate skills that happen to live in the same person. It's one skill:
          understand how the whole thing works, own it from top to bottom, and just ship it."
        </blockquote>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== CLOSING ===== -->
      <section class="about-closing">
        <div class="about-closing__inner">
          <div class="about-closing__text">
            <h2 class="about-closing__title">The Bottom Line</h2>
            <p>
              The AI tools that actually work in the real world aren't better because they use
              a smarter model. They're better because of everything around the model: how the
              questions get asked, what information gets passed in, how the answers get checked,
              and whether anyone's paying attention when something goes wrong.
            </p>
            <p>
              This project is proof of that. It's built in a domain where the rules are strict,
              the stakes are real, and 16 people are checking in every week to see if their team
              is still competitive. That's about as good a test as you can get.
